,"Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Askwith, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Beaurepaire, Hampshire, England":"Beaurepaire, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Woolley, Yorkshire, England":"Woolley, Yorkshire, England","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1327–1384":"about 1327–1384","1327–1384":"1327–1384","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1330–1395":"1330–1395","1354–1400":"1354–1400","1357–1384":"1357–1384","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1311–Female":"1311–Deceased","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","Abt 1327":"about 1327","1327":"1327","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1354":"1354","about 1326":"about 1326","about 1354":"about 1354","about 1361":"about 1361","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","of Beaurepaire, Hampshire, England":"Beaurepaire, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Woolley, Yorkshire, England":"Woolley, Yorkshire, England","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vavasour","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: status name for a feudal tenant ranking immediately below a baron, Old French  <i>vavas(s)our</i>,  <i>vavasseur</i>, Latin  <i>vassus vassorum</i> ‘vassal of vassals’."],"variants":[{"name":"Vavasseur","meanings":["English:  see  Vavasour  ."]},{"name":"Bavister","meanings":["English:   Titford   suggests that this is a late variant of   Vavasour  . It would be a dissimilated form of  <i>Vavister</i> and  <i>Vavester</i>, variants of  <i>Vavasour</i> that are evidenced in Lincs, also in Cambs, whence the name spread into Beds. Compare Willa Vavister, 1579 in   IGI   (Scopwick, Lincs); Thomas Vavister, 1615 in   IGI   (Cranwell, Lincs); Mary Vavester, 1708, Joseph Vavisor, 1738 in   IGI   (New Sleaford, Lincs)."]},{"name":"Vawser","meanings":["English: reduced form of   Vavasour  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Vavasour was born about 1327, in Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Mauger Vavasour, was 19 and her mother, Margaret, was 18. She married Sir Bernard Brocas about 1354. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1384, at the age of 58."},"et":{"Abt 1327–1384":"umbes 1327–1384","1327–1384":"1327–1384","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1330–1395":"1330–1395","1354–1400":"1354–1400","1357–1384":"1357–1384","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1311–Female":"1311–Surnud","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1395":"1395","Abt 1327":"umbes 1327","1327":"1327","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1354":"1354","about 1326":"umbes 1326","about 1354":"umbes 1354","about 1361":"umbes 1361","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Askwith, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Askwith, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Beaurepaire, Hampshire, England":"Beaurepaire, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Ki